close_symbols: type of object_ids elements (e.g., uint8 / uint8_t)
explanation:
- OS_FdSet (struct definition): needed to see whether the function actually writes into the object pointed to by Set (presence of object_ids member) — if Set is modified then it cannot be const-qualified.
- type of object_ids elements (e.g., uint8 / uint8_t): needed to confirm the exact member type being written (and whether it is itself declared const), which affects whether Set could be a pointer-to-const.
- OS_CHECK_POINTER macro definition: the macro may perform casts, assignments, or other side-effects that affect whether Set must be non-const; must confirm it only checks for NULL.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex prototype/signature: to confirm it does not take Set (or otherwise modify the object via global/shared state) — if it modified Set the pointer could not be const.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM constant: needed only to fully understand the call to OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex and control flow that leads to modification of Set (verifies when the write occurs).
- OS_SUCCESS constant: required to understand the control flow (whether the write to Set->object_ids is conditional) and thus whether the pointer is potentially modified.
- osal_id_t typedef: to confirm objid is an input value (not a pointer) and does not affect const qualification of Set.
- osal_index_t typedef: to confirm local_id type and that the bit-indexing into object_ids is an integer operation, supporting the determination of whether Set is modified.

These symbols are the minimal items needed to determine if the function writes through the Set pointer or if any called macros/functions require a mutable pointer; if Set (or its members) are modified then MISRA's guidance to use const wherever possible does not permit changing the parameter to const.
